<br>
More information on Klez can be found here:<br>
<br>
http://www.trendmicro.com/vinfo/virusencyclo/default5.asp?VName=WORM_KLEZ.H<br>
<br>
I would agree that a format is the best thing to do in this case. If you ever get infected by a virus of this type you have no way of telling what real damage has been caused to the inner workings of your system, and for performance if nothing else, a reinstall is recommended.<br>
<br>
As for your disks, basically the error you are getting sounds to be something to do with the disk being faulty or having marks on them. The way DOS reads the data on a disk drive differs from that of Windows and is possibly the reason why you aren't getting problems through Windows. At first I would have said that the floppy heads had come out of alignment but if it works in Windows then this is probably not the case. It simply sounds as though your disks are suffering from old age.<br>
<br>
The solution to this problem is to firstly buy some new disks from a reputable company like 3M for example (none of these crappy Dixon's own jobs, as they won't last 2 minutes). Then download this file <br>
<br>
http://dos.li5.org/IMGS/WIN98SE.EXE<br>
<br>
This is basically a little program that you run on your system, it asks you to insert an empty disk and it then creates a perfectly bootable diskette which you can use to boot your system.<br>
<br>
Once you have backed up everything you require. Put the disk in and restart your machine. Once you have gone through the process of booting (with CDROM support). You can then type at the command prompt <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   format c: /q/u/s</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> (assuming that C is your primary drive, which it should be). This formats your drive quickly, unconditionally and with the system files (i.e. bootable). <br>
<br>
You should always boot from the disk first and then format <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.bbarden.com/img/em/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    That way you don't have to go to the trouble of locating another boot disk if one fails. Even if it does fail it would be pretty easy to get a local computer company to do you a full Windows 98SE boot disk, so a new hard disk, computer or even motherboard is way out of the question.<br>
<br>
It is possible to make a bootable CD but believe me it is more trouble than it is worth (although I can explain if you like). It is also possibly to set your secondary drive as bootable, but again this is even more trouble than creating a bootable CD.<br>
<br>
Let me know if you need anything else <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.bbarden.com/img/em/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
